solutions.content:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/d1ec8a00-adca-491b-8ac2-a4761be599be_1649438593.232334.png)

Here's a step-by-step explanation for how one could approach and solve this problem. First thing is to identify an approach:

There's no real way to avoid testing every path, so that's the best we'll be able to do; testing every path from start to end and tallying the ones that traverse through every square. We can optimize this, however, which saves us a lot of time. There could theoretically be some mathematical solution to this problem, but to my knowledge that hasn't been discovered yet. A couple notes about the approach:

1. Using Graphs
	Worth mentioning first: the big thing to make this problem *significantly* easier is to use Graphs. The nature of the problem is that you are stepping from one square to another, which begs the use of connected nodes, or Graphs. You could stick to using arrays, which many people mistakenly try. While the time/space complexity is about the same, using arrays is very unintuitive, and it gets very convoluted very quickly. The best and worst case performances are pretty much the same for any approach: having to test every single path. Therefore our choice of data structure between Graphs and Arrays doesn't matter much for time/space, and we're left to choose the option that's easier to code.

	A friend of mine conducts FAANG interviews, and uses pathfinding questions very similar to this problem. He's mentioned that the #1 mistake prospective employees make is using Arrays to keep track of everything instead of Graphs. The vast majority of the time it leads to them getting caught up in a nightmare of Array debugging. Given that you would need to create other Arrays to keep track of things like what squares have been traversed, Graphs are as good or better for space complexity and even time complexity. However in my approach, I'm content to keep an unneccessary Graph[][] array, for the sake of readability and simplicity.

2. DFS vs BFS:
	This is a pathfinding algorithm. With pathfinding, two terms that should always come to mind are DFS, and BFS. DFS (Depth First Search) is the approach of building every path individually to their end, as opposed to BFS (Breadth First Search), which explores every path simultaneously. If the question asked us to find the *shortest* path, then we would want BFS. We would expand in every direction from Start, until a path hits End, at which point we could immediately return. However in this problem, we need to explore *every* path from Start to End, as well as keeping track of certain qualities about each of those paths. Mainly, does a given path from Start to End traverse through every square? So the strategy of choice is DFS.

3. DFS vs BackTracking
	Backtracking and DFS are very similar approaches; arguably identical. DFS implies that you're exploring every single path to its end, whereas Backtracking implies that you'll immediately give up on an incomplete path under certain conditions. Indeed there are certain ways to tell that a path will not satisfy the problem's stipulations (that it goes from Start to End and traverses through every square). This is why this code is better categorized as Backtracking then just DFS (although it's both). This is where we get to optimize.

* Optimizations:
	* Before any Backtracking, we can immediately tell if there are 0 viable paths: if there's a dead end anywhere other than the End and Start squares (e.g. a square with only 1 open square). That would mean our paths would all have to either end there, or skip that square, meaning that no paths could traverse every square from Start to End.
	* If a path reaches the End square prematurely, we immediately stop exploring. That means if a path ever traverses every square, we know it also ends on End, and we can add 1 to the number of viable paths.
	* If a path is ever next to a dead-end square, then the path can *only* go that way. This is similar to the first optimization, though we can create these "dead-end" squares by using all but 1 of the squares around them. If the path branched to any square *other* than that one, then we would leave a dead-end square, meaning all paths from then on won't work.
	* If a path ever reaches an edge, and we've already traversed an edge, we could split our remaining available squares. If there are two squares left and they're opposite one another (e.g. our path hits an edge and we can either go left or right along the edge) then we immediately return 0, because either way the path turns, it will never be able to traverse any squares on the other side.
	* When creating our Graph of nodes, we do so iteratively, through the Array of Graphs all[][]. If you wanted to further optimize you could remove this and fill the Graph recursively. However, this is simple and easy to read, allows us to immediately check for dead-ends easily, and most importantly here, allows for the easy use of print statements. Notice that all[][] isn't used at all in BackTrack(), other than for the Write function.


So now we know we're using an Optimized DFS (or BackTracking) to search through every square. And we're using Graphs to keep track of everything. Time to start coding.

First thing is to declare our Graph data structure:

```

    public class Graph {
		//To keep track of whether we've traversed this square.
        public bool used;

		//A collection of all adjacent squares, represented by their respective Graphs.
        public Graph[] nodes;

		//How many usable nodes are left from the collection above.
        public int count;

		//Default constructor. All nodes start off as unused, with a count of 0.
		//this.nodes always has a length of 4, since every square has at most 4 adjacent squares.
        public Graph() {
            this.used = false;
            this.nodes = new Graph[4];
            this.count = 0;
        }
    }
```
While this.used always starts false, we actually instantiate all obstacles as nodes that are already used prior to BackTracking. The *could* stay null, however this would mean we wouldn't be able to implement the wall-optimization above, since we wouldn't be able to differentiate between nodes along a wall, and nodes that are adjacent to an obstacle. Therefore obstacles are instantiated as used Graphs.
this.nodes[] is also a Graph[4], rather than a List< Graph>[4], since each index nodes[i] corresponds to a direction. If nodes were a List< Graph>, it would be easier to deal with Null nodes (squares on the edge/corner), but the variable length would throw off the directionality. Therefore it's easier to use an Array over a List.
Finally, this.count is initialized to 0, and then appropriately set when we build the Graph.

Next we declare start and end as global variables, and define our main function, UniquePathsIII(int[][] grid):

```
    Graph start, end;

    public int UniquePathsIII(int[][] grid) {
		//Our grid of Graph nodes.
        Graph[][] all = new Graph[grid.Length][];

		//The total number of squares available.
		//This is different from a given Graph.count, which is the total squares that node has available to it.
        int count = 0;

		//Building the Graph.
        for (int i = 0; i < grid.Length; i++) {
            all[i] = new Graph[grid[0].Length];
            for (int j = 0; j < grid[0].Length; j++) {
                all[i][j] = new Graph();

				//If the square is an Obstacle, we set it to used.
				//We also continue to the next square *before* adding to count or adding to any adjacent Graph nodes' counts
                if (grid[i][j] == -1) {
                    all[i][j].used = true;
                    continue;
                }
                count++;
				//If we come across the Start or End, we set the global variables.
                if (grid[i][j] == 1) start = all[i][j];
                if (grid[i][j] == 2) end = all[i][j];

				//We increase the node's count if there are adjacent squares that aren't used (i.e. that aren't obstacles)
                if (i != 0 && !all[i-1][j].used) {
                    all[i][j].nodes[0] = all[i-1][j];
                    all[i][j].count++;
                    all[i-1][j].nodes[2] = all[i][j];
                    all[i-1][j].count++;
                }
                if (j != 0 && !all[i][j-1].used) {
                    all[i][j].nodes[3] = all[i][j-1];
                    all[i][j].count++;
                    all[i][j-1].nodes[1] = all[i][j];
                    all[i][j-1].count++;
                }
            }
        }

		//After building the entire Graph, we then iterate through and look for any square that's a dead end (Graph.count == 1).
		//If it's Start or End then there are still possible paths, but otherwise we immediately return 0.
        foreach (Graph[] i in all) {
            foreach (Graph g in i) {
                if (g != null && g.count == 1 && g != start && g != end) return 0;
            }
        }

		//We then begin building a path, starting at Start.
        return BackTrack(grid, all, start, count-1, false);
    }
```
The main function really only built the Graph, set the global variables, and then checked to make sure there weren't dead ends.

The meat of the code is in BackTrack():
```
	//The only reason BackTrack() takes grid and all is for the Write statement.
	//If Write() is commented out, you can completely remove grid and all.
	//BackTrack() takes s, representing the current square, and count, representing how many squares are left.
	//It also takes wall, which simply records whether or not the current path has ever touched the edge of the grid.
    private int BackTrack(int[][] grid, Graph[][] all, Graph s, int count, bool wall) {

		//Prints the grid, with x's for traversed squares/obstacles, and numbers in each open square
		//representing how many available squares are adjacent to it.
        Write(grid, all, s, count, wall);

		//Return 1 if we traverse every path. This will only be satisfied if the current, last square is End.
        if (count == 0) return 1;
		//If we reach the end before that, immediately return 0.
        if (s == end) return 0;

        int sum = 0;
        s.used = true;

		//We use d (direction) in case there's an adjacent square that's a dead end.
        Graph d = null;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.nodes.Length; i++) if (s.nodes[i] != null) {
            Graph g = s.nodes[i];
			//Every adjacent node's count is decreased by 1 when the current node s is used.
            g.count--;
            //This is what creates the dead ends that we can optimize for with d.
			if (!g.used && g != end && g.count == 1) d = g;
        } else {

			//This in case we hit an edge (s.nodes[i] == null)
			//If we have only opposite squares available to turn, the path returns 0.
            if (wall && s.count == 2 && (s.nodes[(i+2)%4] == null || s.nodes[(i+2)%4].used)) {
                return 0;
            }
            wall = true;
        }

		//If we didn't create a dead-end, we explore all of the curren't square's available adjacent squares (Graph g in s.nodes).
        if (d == null) {
            foreach (Graph g in s.nodes) {
                if (g != null && !g.used) {
                    sum += BackTrack(grid, all, g, count-1, false);
                }
            }
			//If a dead-end was found, we ignore all other possible paths, since any valid path *must* traverse through d.
        } else sum += BackTrack(grid, all, d, count-1, false);

		//Finally, when we've explored every path that uses s, we set it to unused again and add 1 back to its adjacent squares' counts.
        foreach (Graph g in s.nodes) if (g != null) g.count++;
        s.used = false;

		//Finally we return sum, which is added to the previous path's sum, and so-on,
		//until we get to the top BackTrack() call, from Start, which has a total sum of all possible paths.
        return sum;
    }
```

In total this is roughly O(3<sup>n</sup>) Time complexity, since each square has at most 3 possible squares to step to. Other than Start, one of its adjacent squares is already used. Space complexity is O(n), since every Graph node is O(1) space complexity, and there are n nodes. I hope this helped someone. Feel free to copy paste this and look at the print statements. It helps quite a bit to see the DFS step-by-step.

Here is all of the code together, along with Write():
```
public class Solution {

    public class Graph {
        public bool used;
        public Graph[] nodes;
        public int count;
        public Graph() {
            this.used = false;
            this.nodes = new Graph[4];
            this.count = 0;
        }
    }

    Graph start, end;

    public int UniquePathsIII(int[][] grid) {
        Graph[][] all = new Graph[grid.Length][];
        int count = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < grid.Length; i++) {
            all[i] = new Graph[grid[0].Length];
            for (int j = 0; j < grid[0].Length; j++) {
                all[i][j] = new Graph();
                if (grid[i][j] == -1) {
                    all[i][j].used = true;
                    continue;
                }
                count++;
                if (grid[i][j] == 1) start = all[i][j];
                if (grid[i][j] == 2) end = all[i][j];
                if (i != 0 && !all[i-1][j].used) {
                    all[i][j].nodes[0] = all[i-1][j];
                    all[i][j].count++;
                    all[i-1][j].nodes[2] = all[i][j];
                    all[i-1][j].count++;
                }
                if (j != 0 && !all[i][j-1].used) {
                    all[i][j].nodes[3] = all[i][j-1];
                    all[i][j].count++;
                    all[i][j-1].nodes[1] = all[i][j];
                    all[i][j-1].count++;
                }
            }
        }
        foreach (Graph[] i in all) {
            foreach (Graph g in i) {
                if (g != null && g.count == 1 && g != start && g != end) return 0;
            }
        }
        return BackTrack(grid, all, start, count-1, false);
    }

    private int BackTrack(int[][] grid, Graph[][] all, Graph s, int count, bool wall) {
        //Write(grid, all, s, count, wall);
        if (count == 0) return 1;
        if (s == end) return 0;
        int sum = 0;
        s.used = true;
        Graph d = null;
        for (int i = 0; i < s.nodes.Length; i++) if (s.nodes[i] != null) {
            Graph g = s.nodes[i];
            g.count--;
            if (!g.used && g != end && g.count == 1) d = g;
        } else {
            if (wall && s.count == 2 && (s.nodes[(i+2)%4] == null || s.nodes[(i+2)%4].used)) {
                return 0;
            }
            wall = true;
        }
        if (d == null) {
            foreach (Graph g in s.nodes) {
                if (g != null && !g.used) {
                    sum += BackTrack(grid, all, g, count-1, false);
                }
            }
        } else sum += BackTrack(grid, all, d, count-1, false);
        foreach (Graph g in s.nodes) if (g != null) g.count++;
        s.used = false;
        return sum;
    }
    private void Write(int[][] grid, Graph[][] all, Graph s, int count, bool wall) {
        foreach (Graph[] i in all) {
            foreach (Graph g in i) {
                if (g == null) {
                    Console.Write(0 + ", ");
                    continue;
                }
                Console.Write((s == g || g.used? "x" : g.count) + ", ");
            }
            Console.WriteLine();
