solutions.content:
* Iterate through the grid once, record the start coordinate and count the number of total "non-obstacle" cells.
*  Using a boolean visited array, we could simply mark the obstacles as "visited" so that in helper method, if we meet the obstacle, return directly.

Helper Method:
* In helper method, the two base cases are: 
	* first check if the index i,j is still within boundary or if the cell has been visited. If not, return directly. 
	* Otherwise, check when reach the end `2` if `remain` equals 1, if so, we've found a new path. `count += 1` and return. 
* Recursive case is:
	* mark current cell as visited, visit all four directions.
	* after recursion, put the cell back to unvisited.

```
class Solution {
    int count = 0;
    public int uniquePathsIII(int[][] grid) {
        int m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length;
        boolean[][] visited = new boolean[m][n];
        int r = 0, c = 0; // start point
        int remain = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) {
                if (grid[i][j] >= 0) {
                    remain++;
                    if (grid[i][j] == 1){
                        r = i;
                        c = j;
                    } 
                } else {
                    visited[i][j] = true;
                }
            }
        }
        helper(grid, r, c, remain, visited);
        return count;
    }

    private void helper(int[][]grid, int i, int j, int remain, boolean[][] visited) {
        if (i < 0 || j < 0 || i >= visited.length || j >= visited[0].length || visited[i][j] == true) {
            return;
        }
        if (grid[i][j] == 2 && remain == 1) {
            this.count+=1;
            return;
        }
        visited[i][j] = true;

        helper(grid, i+1, j, remain - 1, visited);
        helper(grid, i-1, j, remain - 1, visited);
        helper(grid, i, j+1, remain - 1, visited);
        helper(grid, i, j-1, remain - 1, visited);

        visited[i][j] = false;
    }
}
```

